CSS Variables (Custom Properties)
CSS variables (also known as custom properties) are a powerful feature introduced in CSS3 that allows you to define and reuse values throughout your stylesheet. They provide a flexible and efficient way to maintain consistency and make your CSS more maintainable.

How CSS Variables Work
Define variables: Use the -- prefix to define variables. For example, --primary-color: blue;.
Use variables: Refer to variables using the var() function. For example, color: var(--primary-color);.
Example: Using CSS Variables
HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>CSS Variables Example</title>
    <style>
        :root {
            --primary-color: blue;
            --secondary-color: red;
            --font-size: 18px;
        }

        .button {
            background-color: var(--primary-color);
            color: var(--secondary-color);
            font-size: var(--font-size);
            padding: 10px 20px;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <button class="button">Click me</button>
</body>
</html>
Use code with caution.

Changing Variable Values
To change the value of a CSS variable, you can modify its definition in the :root selector or use JavaScript to dynamically update it.

Example using JavaScript:

JavaScript
const button = document.querySelector('.button');
const root = document.documentElement;

root.style.setProperty('--primary-color', 'green');
root.style.setProperty('--secondary-color', 'white');
root.style.setProperty('--font-size', '24px');
Use code with caution.

Explanation:

The :root selector targets the root element of the HTML document.
The setProperty() method is used to update the value of the specified variable.
By changing the variable values, the styles of all elements that reference those variables will be automatically updated, ensuring consistency throughout your stylesheet.

Benefits of CSS Variables
Improved maintainability: By centralizing variable definitions, it's easier to make global changes to your styles.
Enhanced flexibility: Variables allow you to create dynamic styles that can be easily customized.
Better performance: Using variables can reduce the number of CSS rules that need to be recalculated, leading to improved performance.
CSS variables are a valuable tool for creating efficient and maintainable stylesheets. By understanding how to define and use them, you can enhance the flexibility and customization of your web designs.